<span key="58349b6b5af440b6838231b69abec426"><span offset-key="58349b6b5af440b6838231b69abec426:0"><span slate-zero-width="z">â€‹</span></span></span><a href="https://github.com" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="6877a13d1b1341f68762eab1ba274eb4" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-5716_259-5717-237__"><span data-key="b7f5d756b2054fb398bb270d4a1cd1e3"><strong>GitHub (Links to an external site.)</strong></span></span></a><span key="e7f8dbf187714882be462150be5f7b64"><span offset-key="e7f8dbf187714882be462150be5f7b64:0"> is an online repository hosting service and is the most commonly used of its kind in the software industry. <span key="5d65d86b4b884a439e655a5654152be2"><span offset-key="5d65d86b4b884a439e655a5654152be2:0">Branching</span></span>

<span key="f463ba2e1b27495b8a04bbcd6641d72a"><span offset-key="f463ba2e1b27495b8a04bbcd6641d72a:0">This is something you already know how to do. Using </span>`git checkout -b <your-branch-name>`<span offset-key="f463ba2e1b27495b8a04bbcd6641d72a:2"> is how we create new branches to work off of.</span></span>

<span key="4ea61c671d89462aab68f54b84663b37"><span offset-key="4ea61c671d89462aab68f54b84663b37:0">In Labs, </span>**we require that all branches be broken off of the** **`main`** **branch in your repositories.**<span offset-key="4ea61c671d89462aab68f54b84663b37:4"> This will allow for a clean development flow.</span></span>

<span key="66558e44006b4b19880229fc7f1d8061"><span offset-key="66558e44006b4b19880229fc7f1d8061:0">There are two types of branches you'll create during your time in Lambda School Labs, and we ask that you follow a specific naming convention for each flow:</span></span>

1.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height:24px">1.</span>
    <span key="74b22280bd6c429e8155f367a17ddf6d">**Feature**<span offset-key="74b22280bd6c429e8155f367a17ddf6d:1"> branches: </span>`feature/description-description-of-the-feature`</span>

    -   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

        <span key="f96ad93e444140828524c15d73afee31">*Example*<span offset-key="f96ad93e444140828524c15d73afee31:1">: If I needed to implement a login form for my app, my branch name would be </span>`feature/login-form`</span>

2.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height:24px">2.</span>
    <span key="e456f74449f64481a2cc68dc2204b9a4">**Bug**<span offset-key="e456f74449f64481a2cc68dc2204b9a4:1"> branches: </span>`bug/description-of-bug`</span>

    -   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

        <span key="d606d5ca13de40f4867c84cf04a1f9d7">*Example*<span offset-key="d606d5ca13de40f4867c84cf04a1f9d7:1">: If I was fixing the login form button, my branch name would be </span>`bug/login-submit-handler`</span>

<span key="dab65ecadf914387b22a1693e3e74ca8"><span offset-key="dab65ecadf914387b22a1693e3e74ca8:0">The reason for segmenting everything into these two simple branching flows is so that you don't have a messy </span>**git history**<span offset-key="dab65ecadf914387b22a1693e3e74ca8:2">â€”the chronological log of changes that were made to your project's code over time.</span></span>

<span key="d1c0f29f04ba4a988133a89e1ae55c7d"><span offset-key="d1c0f29f04ba4a988133a89e1ae55c7d:0">In the real world, you might see more complex and/or specific strategies, depending on how your team operates. Knowing this flow will help you be prepared for any strategy a team deems necessary to deploy.</span></span>

<span key="d400c43fe2c5443fa4a106f4af3b5d99"><span offset-key="d400c43fe2c5443fa4a106f4af3b5d99:0"><span slate-zero-width="n">â€‹</span></span></span>

<span key="076baafbceb4453682eaff58b9220e22"><span offset-key="076baafbceb4453682eaff58b9220e22:0"><span slate-zero-width="n">â€‹</span></span></span>

# 

<span key="5025dbed6cf14a3ab3c8244ba96a6501"><span offset-key="5025dbed6cf14a3ab3c8244ba96a6501:0">Creating Pull Requests and Draft Pull Requests</span></span>

## 

<span key="2a42a180d5384900a4e8a95f0110fb36"><span offset-key="2a42a180d5384900a4e8a95f0110fb36:0">Forking vs. Cloning</span></span>

<span key="1df34e674465445b93ec1f4182831c11"><span offset-key="1df34e674465445b93ec1f4182831c11:0">In order to submit your code for review and eventually merge your code into the main branch of your project's repository, you'll need to open a pull request.</span></span>

<span key="aa9ba4dc28bf4a2cb28e35e766d0aa2d"><span offset-key="aa9ba4dc28bf4a2cb28e35e766d0aa2d:0">This step is one you're familiar with at this point in your Lambda School journey. The main difference between what you've been doing in core instruction versus what we do here in Labs is that </span>**you won't fork your project's repositories**<span offset-key="aa9ba4dc28bf4a2cb28e35e766d0aa2d:2">â€”instead, you'll </span>**clone**<span offset-key="aa9ba4dc28bf4a2cb28e35e766d0aa2d:4"> them, working within the same GitHub organization.</span></span>

<span key="d158c74b5b684f8ea783e46f2f0aec72"><span offset-key="d158c74b5b684f8ea783e46f2f0aec72:0">Forking is a natural choice for open source contributions to product repositories in GitHub organizations that you don't belong to. Here in Labs, you'll be part of the Lambda School Labs GitHub organization. You've been granted write access to the repos with which you'll be working.</span></span>

<span key="b4f2a06ccfc44e15aab4ef8e79c02f65"><span offset-key="b4f2a06ccfc44e15aab4ef8e79c02f65:0">Thus, in Labs, </span>**you'll never need to fork a repository**<span offset-key="b4f2a06ccfc44e15aab4ef8e79c02f65:2">â€”except perhaps at the very end of your project, when you can decide to fork your project repos to keep a copy of your work in that state after you leave Labs (note that </span>**if you don't do this, you'll lose access to the project code!**<span offset-key="b4f2a06ccfc44e15aab4ef8e79c02f65:4">).</span></span>

## 

<span key="7f5d04d74ec746a797fa96dbcda4c433"><span offset-key="7f5d04d74ec746a797fa96dbcda4c433:0">Draft Pull Requests</span></span>

<span key="81a2015ea613485bb8fcb363aa503b2c"><span offset-key="81a2015ea613485bb8fcb363aa503b2c:0">A </span></span><a href="https://github.blog/2019-02-14-introducing-draft-pull-requests/" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="aaf5e15384b042f081173ef71fe86842" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-5716_259-5717-237__"><span data-key="a1ded23a2d2b41d58dc3eae266b98d4d"><strong>draft pull request (Links to an external site.)</strong></span></span></a><span key="9e9e01934fbf4fd09970a8185f1373a7"><span offset-key="9e9e01934fbf4fd09970a8185f1373a7:0"> is a feature introduced by GitHub in early 2019 that lets you easily share and track a </span>**work in progress**<span offset-key="9e9e01934fbf4fd09970a8185f1373a7:2">. As you go through the process of opening a pull request, you can designate it as a draft, which comes with many benefits.</span></span>

<span key="9c997b4afbd648ed9ce7e2c32e63fd0d"><span offset-key="9c997b4afbd648ed9ce7e2c32e63fd0d:0">Draft pull requests can't be merged, so you won't accidentally merge in changes that aren't ready. When you submit draft pull requests, you also won't spam any "code owners" (in Labs, your Release Manager!) with spurious notifications.</span></span>

<span key="d6b607916b664f80802e9be063cf44da"><span offset-key="d6b607916b664f80802e9be063cf44da:0">But opening a draft pull request </span>*will*<span offset-key="d6b607916b664f80802e9be063cf44da:2"> let you easily show your work and consolidate a conversation around it as it progresses. We </span>**highly recommend**<span offset-key="d6b607916b664f80802e9be063cf44da:4"> using draft pull requests in Labs to maximize visibility into your work and facilitate the number one factor in the success of a project: </span>**communication**<span offset-key="d6b607916b664f80802e9be063cf44da:6">.</span></span>

##

# 

<span key="1aa8a868d286451aa038b590e25c02e1"><span offset-key="1aa8a868d286451aa038b590e25c02e1:0">Rebasing</span></span>

<span key="3d2ac569e8d64e6a896273bc2240f509"><span offset-key="3d2ac569e8d64e6a896273bc2240f509:0">Throughout your career, you'll encounter a variety of merging strategies. We require you use a </span></span><a href="https://docs.labs.lambdaschool.com/guides/coding/git-rebase" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="3f4a5a1f65914b19a7690e9475c3aa00" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-5716_259-5717-237__"><span data-key="923c3dcab517422da057b9241b40ca26"><span data-offset-key="923c3dcab517422da057b9241b40ca26:0">Git Rebase (Links to an external site.)</span></span></span></a><span key="1bdeed2ff1f846a18aaac04ce2c61d70"><span offset-key="1bdeed2ff1f846a18aaac04ce2c61d70:0"> strategy for your team's workflow in Labs.</span></span>

<span key="6077a291d0a348f390b97837f074f492"><span offset-key="6077a291d0a348f390b97837f074f492:0">How teams merge code is a </span>*hotly*<span offset-key="6077a291d0a348f390b97837f074f492:2"> debated topic in the industry, but here in Lambda School Labs, we ask that you use a </span>`rebase`<span offset-key="6077a291d0a348f390b97837f074f492:4"> strategy to keep your git commit history clean. Although there are other strategies for merging code across development teams, rebase is the dominantly accepted practice in the industry today.</span></span>

## 

<span key="98da197c9adf4e19822dd042aa74c60e">**Why Rebase?**</span>

<span key="436c3301a5c74548a97d5596dc29e85d"><span offset-key="436c3301a5c74548a97d5596dc29e85d:0">On occasion, you'll find that you've been working on a feature branch and you need to merge in changes from the main branch. This could just be a final step before you push a series of commits to GitHub in order to create a pull request (PR). Or, maybe it's to update your branch from </span>`main`<span offset-key="436c3301a5c74548a97d5596dc29e85d:2"> after a day or so of work.</span></span>

<span key="e11d1884f53649d6966b9d0ebf56f9d6"><span offset-key="e11d1884f53649d6966b9d0ebf56f9d6:0">With rebasing, you approach this situation by finding the "common ancestor" of the main and feature branch, and then "replaying" the commits made since then to create a new base commit.</span></span>

<span key="f42b6974f7bb4578b5cd6dd83c46f969"><span offset-key="f42b6974f7bb4578b5cd6dd83c46f969:0">Sound complicated? Here's how it works:</span></span>

## 

<span key="9149a57d6aa341ada53aef916940c045">**How to Rebase**</span>

<span key="241bfe99d9fb42569ac09f679a42ad67"><span offset-key="241bfe99d9fb42569ac09f679a42ad67:0">These steps are similar to what the "Rebase and Merge" action does on GitHub. </span>**(You should always use this if "Squash and Merge" isn't available.)**</span>

1.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height:24px">1.</span>
    <span key="15e79b97e05041b7b3eb33aa169b937a"><span offset-key="15e79b97e05041b7b3eb33aa169b937a:0">Make sure all changes are committed to your feature branch.</span></span>

2.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height:24px">2.</span>
    <span key="b38051a3d71d4149aec98f13b1e53768"><span offset-key="b38051a3d71d4149aec98f13b1e53768:0">Update your local master branch:</span></span>

    -   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

        <span key="44b1f5d6a0d14955926e2e23ea9bee25">`> git checkout master`</span>

    -   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

        <span key="5b6a15a210f047db829fbb67cf3a3652">`> git pull origin master`</span>

3.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height:24px">3.</span>
    <span key="049506567be14c8eb7e87c6d668225b1"><span offset-key="049506567be14c8eb7e87c6d668225b1:0">Go back to your feature branch:</span></span>

    -   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

        <span key="07f4933d968c4444b8b44e510715c22c">`> git checkout feature-branch`</span>

4.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height:24px">4.</span>
    <span key="e437770f80194650a08c99731186d12b"><span offset-key="e437770f80194650a08c99731186d12b:0">Now we can rebase the feature branch onto </span>`master`<span offset-key="e437770f80194650a08c99731186d12b:2">:</span></span>

    -   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

        <span key="8ab065ad2d8d4ddfb969061e55ce12ef">`> git rebase master`</span>

    -   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

        <span key="bf8abeb1e9e146e4b581a1d0e501e9f2"><span offset-key="bf8abeb1e9e146e4b581a1d0e501e9f2:0">Result: </span>`First, rewinding head to replay your work on top of it...`<span offset-key="bf8abeb1e9e146e4b581a1d0e501e9f2:2"> </span>`Applying: added staged command`</span>

5.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height:24px">5.</span>
    <span key="638ec4d766424fd095b971d8072bfb3c"><span offset-key="638ec4d766424fd095b971d8072bfb3c:0">Your commits will now show in the git log after the commits merged from master.</span></span>

<span key="ccf5cec0d1cc4a36895c8d791958e7ad"><span offset-key="ccf5cec0d1cc4a36895c8d791958e7ad:0"> </span></span>

<span key="8f2a5fc4cc4840839556bd6412ba463c"><span offset-key="8f2a5fc4cc4840839556bd6412ba463c:0">For more information, see our entry on Git Rebase in </span></span><a href="https://docs.labs.lambdaschool.com/guides/coding/git-rebase" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="66689ad6cd2f44b0bda0092dd6132812" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-5716_259-5717-237__"><span data-key="3a018a37bf3b47d380caf1c7d1c6533d"><span data-offset-key="3a018a37bf3b47d380caf1c7d1c6533d:0">the Labs Guides (Links to an external site.)</span></span></span></a><span key="036e84cfb5df45cd94f2b043308f0ed9"><span offset-key="036e84cfb5df45cd94f2b043308f0ed9:0">.</span></span>

# 

<span key="77e675b6cd2e4d59b6ce261fe011a946"><span offset-key="77e675b6cd2e4d59b6ce261fe011a946:0">Merge Conflicts</span></span>

## 

<span key="28d96239af5b4cf08596fcf40aa58f6e"><span offset-key="28d96239af5b4cf08596fcf40aa58f6e:0">What are Merge Conflicts?</span></span>

<span key="a08b69eb8c2546ff8165430e95f5d0d3">**Merge conflicts**<span offset-key="a08b69eb8c2546ff8165430e95f5d0d3:1"> occur within a development team's workflow when two developers try and update the same line of code in the same file. When this happens, git will inform you that you have a merge conflict.</span></span>

<span key="2cddaf28dd3e46129551d0ba9900f884"><span offset-key="2cddaf28dd3e46129551d0ba9900f884:0">You need to resolve merge conflicts before pushing to your branch and rebasing your code into </span>`main`<span offset-key="2cddaf28dd3e46129551d0ba9900f884:2">.</span></span>

<span key="dc4dea6e66d746e48e088de3e62a9f93"><span offset-key="dc4dea6e66d746e48e088de3e62a9f93:0">When a merge conflict occurs, git will write some text directly into the file where the conflict exists. You'll need to:</span></span>

1.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height:24px">1.</span>
    <span key="94d08afdf7ab41839e3c5af68f27ddc2"><span offset-key="94d08afdf7ab41839e3c5af68f27ddc2:0">Go into that file and remove that inserted text</span></span>

2.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height:24px">2.</span>
    <span key="d99f1ca1659e41428410519e348c66f5"><span offset-key="d99f1ca1659e41428410519e348c66f5:0">Specify which lines of code you want to live in your branch</span></span>

<span key="1a5cec743f5449bfaf1eb657738b2900"><span offset-key="1a5cec743f5449bfaf1eb657738b2900:0"> </span></span>

<span key="8d6c7effb2884d299cadd05ffecd564e"><span offset-key="8d6c7effb2884d299cadd05ffecd564e:0">ðŸ’¡ Pro tip: VSCode (and other IDEs) have great merge conflict tools built in. We </span>**highly**<span offset-key="8d6c7effb2884d299cadd05ffecd564e:2"> recommend you resolve any merge conflicts that arise with another developer presentâ€”preferably the developer whose code you're conflicting with!</span></span>

## 

<span key="df8542e2cbbf4ac5a4510a1a0cf173ff"><span offset-key="df8542e2cbbf4ac5a4510a1a0cf173ff:0">Dealing With Merge Conflicts</span></span>

# 

<span key="4a5b725251e14c61b7677419d5c30c1b"><span offset-key="4a5b725251e14c61b7677419d5c30c1b:0">Reviewing Pull Requests</span></span>

<span key="22db4246d9c64668a8b2ea595f5e670e"><span offset-key="22db4246d9c64668a8b2ea595f5e670e:0">Here in Lambda School Labs, we firmly believe that </span>**clean code lives and dies by authoring and reviewing high-quality pull requests**<span offset-key="22db4246d9c64668a8b2ea595f5e670e:2">.</span></span>

<span key="21438552402441dd9f2603ece895bb0d"><span offset-key="21438552402441dd9f2603ece895bb0d:0">In Labs, the pull request is the final step between your development lifecycle and deployment. Since it's your final step to get your code pushed to production, it's of the utmost importance that you try your hardest to ensure that the quality of the code you'll be submitting is held to the highest standard possible.</span></span>

## 

<span key="3bd844a764a54b9d98b75c281e70bf40"><span offset-key="3bd844a764a54b9d98b75c281e70bf40:0">Pull Request Requirements in Labs</span></span>

<span key="9f970b57e08640779bbce00a39b071dc"><span offset-key="9f970b57e08640779bbce00a39b071dc:0">We require that each pull request:</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="4decd467c8c64cf1941761dd948935ac"><span offset-key="4decd467c8c64cf1941761dd948935ac:0">contains a </span>**brief, 2â€“5 minute**<span offset-key="4decd467c8c64cf1941761dd948935ac:2"> video walkthrough presenting your work</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="8aa94924bb8146d2b9e9d1280b53f62e"><span offset-key="8aa94924bb8146d2b9e9d1280b53f62e:0">is well documented and provides links to any supporting documentsâ€”like Trello cards, design artifacts, or further documentation to ensure everyone knows </span>**why**<span offset-key="8aa94924bb8146d2b9e9d1280b53f62e:2"> the pull request was necessary.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="99e0238c691a4456befe410ec6afdb6a"><span offset-key="99e0238c691a4456befe410ec6afdb6a:0">has commits that are relevant to what has changed.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="fee774aa72254a9a8d9e61ed903340d1"><span offset-key="fee774aa72254a9a8d9e61ed903340d1:0">contains work relevant to the pull request description.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="1c3b4c2de1714429b56e52a065cbe80d"><span offset-key="1c3b4c2de1714429b56e52a065cbe80d:0">has been adequately </span>**reviewed by at least 2 peers and your release manager**<span offset-key="1c3b4c2de1714429b56e52a065cbe80d:2">. Your release manager has final approval, and your code will not be merged into </span>`main`<span offset-key="1c3b4c2de1714429b56e52a065cbe80d:4"> unless your release manager has approved it.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="b53cda405268490faa03965ac3201519"><span offset-key="b53cda405268490faa03965ac3201519:0">contains maintainable code that has been formatted to your product specifications.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="dc224fd03a52496da59deae5b687df28"><span offset-key="dc224fd03a52496da59deae5b687df28:0">follows industry best practices.</span></span>

<span key="24273005cd5147ce829d68ce3f103c03"><span offset-key="24273005cd5147ce829d68ce3f103c03:0">Not only do pull requests highlight the code you writeâ€”</span>**they're the best mechanism for a hiring manager get a glimpse into how you work as an effective member of a dev team.**<span offset-key="24273005cd5147ce829d68ce3f103c03:2"> Treat them as professionally as you'd like to be treated in the industry.</span></span>

### 

<span key="da2bdfab10a74800bc9f1ba064f16786"><span offset-key="da2bdfab10a74800bc9f1ba064f16786:0">The Pull Request Rubric</span></span>

<span key="095af2f122d14ebb9833182905cd5863"><span offset-key="095af2f122d14ebb9833182905cd5863:0">Follow our rubric to help you practice authoring and reviewing proper pull requests. Throughout Labs, we'll hold regular Pull Request Critique sessions, where your engineering manager will breakdown the work you've done and how you've worked to make it clear to reviewers.</span></span>

<span key="079d8408ed4b4850ac76c91668191059"><span offset-key="079d8408ed4b4850ac76c91668191059:0"><span slate-zero-width="z">â€‹</span></span></span><a href="https://www.notion.so/lambdaschool/1fc04e4fedeb429ba873b7c68d281707?v=74054da7991341c0bf970f39410c43da" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="aa1f473b99994fb194ce164de866a044" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-5716_259-5717-237__"><span data-key="6633149ef5d14038b8a17d6a3725c44e"><strong>Pull Request Rubric</strong></span></span></a><span key="09b262464653477bbaab05c68621c709"><span offset-key="09b262464653477bbaab05c68621c709:0"><span slate-zero-width="z">â€‹</span></span></span>

<span key="f924cf3e578b4a31ae894b8fe09c7d68"><span offset-key="f924cf3e578b4a31ae894b8fe09c7d68:0"><span slate-zero-width="n">â€‹</span></span></span>

# 

<span key="e4d7f51cfa7d4dd4a4aeb4be2bb331c6"><span offset-key="e4d7f51cfa7d4dd4a4aeb4be2bb331c6:0">Pull Request Rubric</span></span>

<span key="d47d22c44ecd4318af879951a802c7c0"><span offset-key="d47d22c44ecd4318af879951a802c7c0:0">Objective</span></span>

<span key="c9206ed93bfe49178e5231ae0d83e527"><span offset-key="c9206ed93bfe49178e5231ae0d83e527:0">Description</span></span>

<span key="36d8a98e5051462fae19f0a962e5e427"><span offset-key="36d8a98e5051462fae19f0a962e5e427:0">1-3 (Not Passing)</span></span>

<span key="2e4464439cb443dba9eb827ad2d81b8c"><span offset-key="2e4464439cb443dba9eb827ad2d81b8c:0">4 (Passing)</span></span>

<span key="178c85c1c8cf4378a1d1958a6a9c3ecd"><span offset-key="178c85c1c8cf4378a1d1958a6a9c3ecd:0">5-7 (Exceptional)</span></span>

<span key="fd49185b280240c699d79fdf5ce1a5f3"><span offset-key="fd49185b280240c699d79fdf5ce1a5f3:0"><span slate-zero-width="z">â€‹</span></span></span><a href="https://www.notion.so/Clearly-documents-the-motivation-and-what-changed-7bde9cc88e8241ee8d802b5d6ff146fa" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="6798f8c893fd44019f6790f022501f28" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-5716_259-5717-237__"><span data-key="86626a10ae4a4f09957c1acd559d2e24"><span data-offset-key="86626a10ae4a4f09957c1acd559d2e24:0">Clearly documents the motivation and what changed</span></span></span></a><span key="506763ea87dc4bf8bd4f24d7fb50b047"><span offset-key="506763ea87dc4bf8bd4f24d7fb50b047:0"><span slate-zero-width="z">â€‹</span></span></span>

<span key="d51c15aa99d8418da9c4a8d677d3db30"><span offset-key="d51c15aa99d8418da9c4a8d677d3db30:0">Is it clear why the pull request exists? Does it link to supporting documentation (user story, product roadmap, design) to give broader context? Is the code itself appropriately commented?</span></span>

<span key="5ff0130f24e448429e199b453a828029"><span offset-key="5ff0130f24e448429e199b453a828029:0">The PR description is either blank or only contains the boilerplate PR template or unchecked checklist items. Code comments aren't used, even when they would be helpful.</span></span>

<span key="3c78d59706c64dc4aa5f31775b1aa91b"><span offset-key="3c78d59706c64dc4aa5f31775b1aa91b:0">The PR description outlines the motivation for the feature and/or links to a user story or other document describing the purpose of the feature.</span></span>

<span key="1d3f5cd39ba74996b1364945f51e8727"><span offset-key="1d3f5cd39ba74996b1364945f51e8727:0">The PR description includes a clear rationale for the feature, or a screenshot showing either the intended state or completed state of the feature, and gives additional context about changes made in the PR.</span></span>

<span key="a54064638c8447449a13b509ef20d3bb"><span offset-key="a54064638c8447449a13b509ef20d3bb:0"><span slate-zero-width="z">â€‹</span></span></span><a href="https://www.notion.so/Atomic-well-named-commits-cb361314bff941fbaa6bbf8f325bfea7" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="6ec3d11775db47fda7bf5cb248407c34" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-5716_259-5717-237__"><span data-key="c427ca1bdc644b34b4286e99ccd2b0bd"><span data-offset-key="c427ca1bdc644b34b4286e99ccd2b0bd:0">Atomic, well-named commits</span></span></span></a><span key="db7fde0aa4644aef9bfd6afbbf136e97"><span offset-key="db7fde0aa4644aef9bfd6afbbf136e97:0"><span slate-zero-width="z">â€‹</span></span></span>

<span key="d09241b11e9f457db0647dc0fb927131"><span offset-key="d09241b11e9f457db0647dc0fb927131:0">Does the pull request consist of small commits with clear titles? Do all commits have relevant and sensible messages of what was changed?</span></span>

<span key="7e4194923c7848cdac0900914e0ef968"><span offset-key="7e4194923c7848cdac0900914e0ef968:0">Commits are not named appropriately. Commits have sensible messages. Example. "Updated", "Fixed a bug"</span></span>

<span key="b2d6571605624f87be9ab54dae63ded0"><span offset-key="b2d6571605624f87be9ab54dae63ded0:0">Commits are well named. Commits have descriptive messages relevant to what changed. Some commits are not atomic.</span></span>

<span key="f0f6555a0d97468e801042cad461d3f7"><span offset-key="f0f6555a0d97468e801042cad461d3f7:0">Commits are well named. Commits have descriptive messages. Each commit introduces atomic changes.</span></span>

<span key="057c45044eb949fea308f72b0653a415"><span offset-key="057c45044eb949fea308f72b0653a415:0"><span slate-zero-width="z">â€‹</span></span></span><a href="https://www.notion.so/Appropriately-Scoped-d04fd9f628494c8da1025a40c9b352c5" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="e4de2b196a9d4476968f940fa5417a86" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-5716_259-5717-237__"><span data-key="f14f4c4aa8724a3f9af0ce20942723be"><span data-offset-key="f14f4c4aa8724a3f9af0ce20942723be:0">Appropriately Scoped</span></span></span></a><span key="19248ea3ebc3491a8bafba5ae34f8c48"><span offset-key="19248ea3ebc3491a8bafba5ae34f8c48:0"><span slate-zero-width="z">â€‹</span></span></span>

<span key="eb5d29ff6ed7429d8edadea5c405d0f7"><span offset-key="eb5d29ff6ed7429d8edadea5c405d0f7:0">Is the pull request small enough to review easily? Is it focused on solving a single cohesive problem?</span></span>

<span key="c597111ecb82448495b2636479fd167c"><span offset-key="c597111ecb82448495b2636479fd167c:0">Pull request introduces multiple features or solves multiple problems. PR is unreasonably big with many changed files. Some code changes that are not related to the purpose of the PR</span></span>

<span key="b2b008412b0d42118d93a276214038a4"><span offset-key="b2b008412b0d42118d93a276214038a4:0">PR is relatively small. PR has some minor changes not related to the feature or primary change being introduced.</span></span>

<span key="dcbf2f4156c244ee86a03600d087b38b"><span offset-key="dcbf2f4156c244ee86a03600d087b38b:0">PR is focused on a single problem. PR is small enough and easy to review.</span></span>

<span key="7e7a9891fb114cd8a194347c8bddf129"><span offset-key="7e7a9891fb114cd8a194347c8bddf129:0"><span slate-zero-width="z">â€‹</span></span></span><a href="https://www.notion.so/Adequately-reviewed-e390e4309863446da82907cdd6d76c18" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="4667054d34ad4e34bd59e9792f4672ea" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-5716_259-5717-237__"><span data-key="16ca625d00864dd0a04accb7651c847e"><span data-offset-key="16ca625d00864dd0a04accb7651c847e:0">Adequately reviewed</span></span></span></a><span key="fa239447f9dc4138afa33a6766a6a61a"><span offset-key="fa239447f9dc4138afa33a6766a6a61a:0"><span slate-zero-width="z">â€‹</span></span></span>

<span key="84fa298e519e4ac9a0cc7210790a56a6"><span offset-key="84fa298e519e4ac9a0cc7210790a56a6:0">Has the pull request been reviewed by at least two team members? Your release manager will be the final reviewer of the pull request. Did they leave any comments or suggestions? Were those suggestions acted on?</span></span>

<span key="633120c1daae43699f5e7fb89ea95303"><span offset-key="633120c1daae43699f5e7fb89ea95303:0">PR was merged by the same developer who requested it. The reviewer rejected PR with no comments. PR was initiated again and suggested changes were not addressed.</span></span>

<span key="c5ca9c10238b4612bdb20c00ba321fe0"><span offset-key="c5ca9c10238b4612bdb20c00ba321fe0:0">At least two team members reviewed PRs. Appropriate comments were left in the PR. Suggestions were acted upon.</span></span>

<span key="7b54f438b2d24840b164337fef28553b"><span offset-key="7b54f438b2d24840b164337fef28553b:0">PRs were reviewed by more than one team member. PR requests were sent to multiple reviewers. Active high-quality discussions are evident in PRs.</span></span>

<span key="ccbdfa7bfc034cc1956b2b7f64b4f069"><span offset-key="ccbdfa7bfc034cc1956b2b7f64b4f069:0"><span slate-zero-width="z">â€‹</span></span></span><a href="https://www.notion.so/Code-is-clear-and-maintainable-ff6dbd609cf84aabb825fdd854758986" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="9cb8941c9f014ea98d768a2f9f0df96b" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-5716_259-5717-237__"><span data-key="a1c623fddf7f47a2b1db343b73cca710"><span data-offset-key="a1c623fddf7f47a2b1db343b73cca710:0">Code is clear and maintainable</span></span></span></a><span key="04ad02219dd74e9db7afc75186542e5c"><span offset-key="04ad02219dd74e9db7afc75186542e5c:0"><span slate-zero-width="z">â€‹</span></span></span>

<span key="9fe44f31e7da4933b627d606504b8cf3"><span offset-key="9fe44f31e7da4933b627d606504b8cf3:0">Is the code formatted appropriately? Is there dead code? </span>**<span class="mark r-homxoj" slate-leaf="true" style="background-color:inherit">*logs and print statements have no place in your main branches!*</span>**<span offset-key="9fe44f31e7da4933b627d606504b8cf3:2"> Are there instances of duplicate code? Does code have TODOs committed to main?</span></span>

<span key="9f2ee5253e5a407ea03d44e01f02131a"><span offset-key="9f2ee5253e5a407ea03d44e01f02131a:0">Code has inconsistent formatting. Significant amount of dead code across the codebase. Multiple instances on TODOs in main. Significant amount of duplicated code.</span></span>

<span key="b462f073d78545ce9773b1e863d93258"><span offset-key="b462f073d78545ce9773b1e863d93258:0">Code is consistently formatted. Functions are relatively small. Few instances of duplicate code. Few instances of dead code.</span></span>

<span key="5995331ecd1f40db868e6674c6fa50a7"><span offset-key="5995331ecd1f40db868e6674c6fa50a7:0">Code is consistently formatted. Has config files to enforce linting and formatting. No instance on duplicate code.</span></span>

<span key="3ad00000a4a24922a014686e5d98e35b"><span offset-key="3ad00000a4a24922a014686e5d98e35b:0"><span slate-zero-width="z">â€‹</span></span></span><a href="https://www.notion.so/Code-is-idiomatic-3ba62709ad784917973adcc74cfc3248" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="d68117738abb4e1e97da24135ce5eb64" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-5716_259-5717-237__"><span data-key="717f9ec4d75d4d9cbd1c98f9eea6e01c"><span data-offset-key="717f9ec4d75d4d9cbd1c98f9eea6e01c:0">Code is idiomatic</span></span></span></a><span key="89b001b3bb6942fc8b7f1cb314268e84"><span offset-key="89b001b3bb6942fc8b7f1cb314268e84:0"><span slate-zero-width="z">â€‹</span></span></span>

<span key="35686b7627954e32837990c07374c783"><span offset-key="35686b7627954e32837990c07374c783:0">Does the code follow industry standards for the language, framework, and libraries used?</span></span>

<span key="24c58985280c4a6fbeefb04fe34f917d"><span offset-key="24c58985280c4a6fbeefb04fe34f917d:0">Code consistently does not adhere to best practices for the language, framework or libraries used.</span></span>

<span key="2f37569fd18d4f55a597c5d1801e34fc"><span offset-key="2f37569fd18d4f55a597c5d1801e34fc:0">Code has apparent minor deviations from industry standards.</span></span>

<span key="da51cc48298b462983544123458025ea"><span offset-key="da51cc48298b462983544123458025ea:0">Code follows best practices of language, framework and libraries use. Effort has been made to improve on those practices.</span></span>
